<TEXT>
seven people hospitalized after being 
overcome by carbon monoxide in an ice skating rink were released 
saturday and special precautions were taken to avoid more problems 
the seven were among 25 people sickened by gas emitted from an 
ice grooming machine known as a zamboni during a hockey tournament 
at the rink friday the others were treated with oxygen at the scene 
a faulty exhaust system on the zamboni apparently caused it to 
emit the carbon monoxide which stayed close to the ice said 
tualatin valley fire and rescue department dispatcher rod nodland 
he said the carbon monoxide readings in the arena were at safe 
levels saturday 
john mcbride the valley ice arena general manager said large 
fans were set up saturday to circulate air at the rink and the ice 
grooming machine was fitted with a catalytic converter to reduce its 
emissions 
he theorized that extra refrigeration used to keep the ice solid 
in recent warm weather brought the temperature so low in the arena 
friday that carbon monoxide from the zamboni stayed near the ice and 
wouldnt disperse normally 
this was the second year in a row that carbon monoxide poisoning 
has occurred at the rink during a hockey game for the rose festival 
the citys annual june festival 
paramedics were first alerted to the problems at the rink friday 
night when a parent sought aid for a child that was vomiting 
several children complained of dizziness and nausea and at least 
one child fainted 
dr gregory lorts of providence hospital said one boy brought 
there friday night was treated for 90 minutes in a glassenclosed 
pressurized chamber where pure oxygen was pumped into the boys 
lungs 
because of the relatively low levels of the carbon monoxide in 
fridays incident lorts said it is unlikely that any person at the 
rink would suffer longterm ill effects 
carbon monoxide is odorless tasteless and colorless and is 
produced during combustion 
capt terry kline who headed tualatin valley fire and rescues 
hazardousmaterials team at the rink said initial readings of 
carbon monoxide in the building were 120 to 170 parts per million of 
air 
he said 50 parts per million was considered the maximum 
concentration before people felt sick and 1500 parts per million 
would be lethal 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

