<DOCNO> AP890611-0012 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the communist chinese propaganda machine is 
working at a frenzied pace to portray the bloody military occupation 
of beijing as a heroic operation against counterrevolutionaries 
the saturation campaign serves to shield the government from 
blame for the june 4 massacre in which hundreds perhaps thousands 
of people died when soldiers fired at unarmed citizens supporting a 
movement for a freer society 
word of the assault on the prodemocracy movement quickly spread 
to several large chinese cities where huge crowds took to the 
streets to demand the fall of conservative leaders who ordered the 
military attack 
but hardliners such as senior leader deng xiaoping and premier li 
peng have kept their grip on power supporting their position with 
the propaganda barrage 
the main vehicle for the campaign has been nationwide television 
after a few days of virtual silence on the attack television 
began showing grainy blackandwhite tapes of angry crowds attacking 
soldiers and torching military vehicles color videotapes of similar 
scenes soon appeared often shown dozens of times over several days 
soldiers indiscriminately firing at crowds or crushing people 
with armored vehicles were not shown neither were scenes of 
hospitals filled with the dead and the injured from the withering 
attack on beijings tiananmen square 
the videotapes often did not have sound perhaps so the audience 
could not hear the gunfire or the angry chants of fascists 
directed at the soldiers 
the official theme of soldiers as victims soon was expanded with 
television showing injured troops lying in hospital beds in one 
particularly gruesome scene an evening newscast showed the charred 
bodies of three soldiers burned to death including one who was 
disemboweled 
the campaign also stresses the theme of soldiers as friends 
under guard of rifletoting soldiers propaganda trucks with signs 
reading the peoples army loves the people rolled down beijings 
main streets with loudspeakers blaring 
scenes of soldiers and citizens helping one another have 
dominated television which in recent days have devoted several 
hours of special newscasts daily to present the government line 
on saturday television showed a peasant bringing three huge pigs 
to applauding soldiers the next days evening newscast showed 
troops at an elementary school playing with children and helping 
them clean their classrooms 
the newest phase of the propaganda onslaught has shown dozens of 
scoundrels and counterrevolutionaries under arrest on 
charges of participating in the demonstrations television has shown 
them questioned at gunpoint and signing confessions 
chinese media also has attacked the us governmentfunded voice 
of america which has provided millions of chinese with an 
independent account of the weekend bloodbath 
in another attempt to quell nonofficial accounts television 
saturday urged viewers to turn in a rumormonger who was shown 
giving a bloody account of the attack on sunday the evening news 
reported his capture and the man was shown expressing remorse to 
security officials 
television interviews with citizens applauding the military 
action increased during the weekend 
it gave use great satisfaction to see the peoples liberation 
army go into the city and put down the turmoil said one man 
several people who were interviewed said they were shocked by the 
attacks on soldiers seen on television i was greatly pained to 
see pla soldiers burned to death and beaten to death primary 
school teacher chen qing told a television reporter 
many chinese are skeptical of the statecontrolled media so it is 
impossible to know how many people find the propaganda campaign 
convincing 
not a single person will believe it said one beijing 
university student who claimed he saw more than 10 people shot in 
tiananmen square by soldiers early june 4 
but some chinese who did not see the weekend events themselves 
could find the relentless television accounts persuasive 
in beijing people know what happened but those on the outside 
do not said another beijing university student most chinese 
are peasants they believe what the government says 
</TEXT>
