<TEXT>
the navy is changing the way it stores 
gunpowder for 16inch guns on its iowaclass battleships despite 
indications that powder was not at fault in the fatal blast on the 
battleship iowa 
when the battleship wisconsin heads for maintenance and repairs 
this summer its powder charges 110pound bags will not be 
stored aboard uncooled unventilated barges as the iowas were navy 
officials told the virginianpilot and the ledgerstar of norfolk 
when the iowa went in for similar overhaul during the summer of 
1988 its powder was stored aboard uncooled barges at the yorktown 
naval weapons station on the york river during the hottest part of 
the summer 
in april 47 sailors aboard the iowa were killed when powder 
exploded in the no 2 gun turret during open seas gunnery practice 
before the explosion the no 1 turret had a misfire when the five 
bags of powder used to propel the guns projectile wouldnt ignite 
navy officials have said they do not believe the storage of the 
powder was to blame and are investigating the possibility of 
sabotage nevertheless the charges aboard the iowa have been 
removed and replaced with powder that was stored in 
temperaturecontrolled underground bunkers 
smokeless powder is less stable and less effective if it is 
stored in damp atmosphere or subjected to high temperatures a 
combination of the two is particularly bad according to navy 
manual op5 the services guide to munition storage 
the manual says the powder charges decompose faster at 
temperatures above 70 degrees fahrenheit becoming relatively high 
at 100 degrees fahrenheit and dangerously accelerated at 
temperatures above 110 degrees fahrenheit 
an internal navy report estimates the temperature inside the 
aluminumsided barges used for storage was 25 degrees higher than 
the outside air temperature using that estimate the newspaper 
calculated from national weather service readings for the area that 
the temperature inside the barges could have exceeded 110 degrees on 
66 days at the time the iowas powder was in storage 
the newspaper quoting internal memos from the stations safety 
officer to his superiors said the stations command was urged to 
remove the iowas powder charges from the barges anchored at piers 
on the river bank 
permitting these charges to be stored in the barge for this 
period of time indicates the lack of importance that is placed on 
compliance with the safety requirements set forth in the manual on 
munition storage a september 1988 memo said 
thomas black administrative officer at the yorktown station 
said the wisconsins powder would not be stored at the station the 
largest of the navys six weapon stations 
if it was for a short period it would be something different 
well move it inland and then bring it back when its needed he 
said 
black said additional magazines are being built at the weapons 
station to accommodate more munitions according to the pentagon 
yorktown is the only one of the navys munitions stations that uses 
barges for temporary powder storage 
the navy is continuing its investigation into the explosion and 
has regularly declined to comment on its findings until the 
investigation is complete 
preliminary tests by the navy of the iowa powder have not shown 
any indications of instability according to the pentagon 
</TEXT>
